06423nam a2200817Ia 9789048557424DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485574247 a10.1515/97890485574242doi  a(DE-B1597)678752  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aHQ1148b.E27 2024 7aHIS0370402bisacsh04a305.4209460903223/eng/2024032900aEarly Modern Women's Mobility, Authority, and Agency Across the Spanish Empire /ced. by Anne Cruz, Alejandra Franganillo Álvarez. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aConnected Histories in the Early Modern World ;v900tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Early Modern Women’s Mobility -- tPart I. Transoceanic Crossings -- t1. Inés Muñoz de Ribera: The Making of an Encomendera in Sixteenth-Century Peru -- t2. Isabel Barreto , Navigator of the South Seas and Governor of the Isles of Salomon -- t3. Founding a Convent in the Philippines : Discursive Keys to Travel Narratives of Early Modern Female Religious Communities -- tPart II. Gender Transactions -- t4. Cassandra Grimaldo’s Voyage of No Return: A Genoese Businesswoman in Habsburg Spain -- t5. Trade, Credit, and Marriage : The Mobility of Portuguese Conversa Merchants and Financiers -- t6. Travel and the Illegible Body in the Historia de la Monja Alférez -- t7. Hortense Mancini: A Life on the Run -- tPart III. Transnational Politics -- t8. Seeking Support from the Spanish Monarchy: The Manly Flight of Mary Stuart O’Donnell, Countess of Tyrconnell -- t9. Marie de Rohan, Duchess of Chevreuse : Schemer, Spy, and Wartime Fugitive at the European Courts -- t10. Mobilizing Female Relatives : The Countess of Berlepsch’s Strategies at the Habsburg Courts -- t11. A Cosmopolitan Ambassadress on the Road : Anna Colonna, Marquise of Los Balbases -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe new parameters of a global world in the early modern period gave rise to an expansion of movement that facilitated spatial and social mobility for women of different social ranks. Through their reexamination of archival documents and travel narratives, these essays investigate the opportunities for female mobility across the Spanish Empire, narrating the journeys of women who assumed new and unpredictable roles in distant environments. Some risked transoceanic journeys to hold positions of colonial power, while nuns traveled to found convents. Portuguese and Genoese women financiers and merchants traversed the Mediterranean to command enterprises in different cities. Breaking with tradition, the noblewomen considered in these essays exercised political agency as ambassadresses and diplomatic spies at various European courts. Still other women fled across borders from oppressive marriages or cross-dressed as soldiers to perform adventurous feats in support of imperial causes. Their frequently distorted histories, authored by men, have been revised and rectified by the authors of this volume.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aWomenxSocial conditionsxHistoryy16th century. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsxHistoryy17th century. 0aWomenxTravelxHistoryy16th century. 0aWomenxTravelxHistoryy17th century. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 17th Century.2bisacsh  aEarly modern women, travel, nuns, noblewomen, merchants, Spanish empire, New World.1 aAyán, Carmen Sanz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenjamin, Cortney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergaz, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamino, Mercedes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasado, Cristina Hernández, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz, Anne J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz, Anne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFranganillo Álvarez, Alejandra, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKozák, Valentina Marguerite, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez Anguita, J. Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartos Pérez, María D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPérez-Miguel, Liliana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPérez-Toribio, Montserrat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aÁlvarez, Alejandra Franganillo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311133235240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048557424?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048557424423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048557424/original  a978-3-11-133235-2  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles